n Jones]] || || {{suboff|90+1}}\n|-\n|CM ||'''7''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Cristian Roldan]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''4''' ||{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Gustav Svensson]]\n|-\n|RW ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|URU}} [[Nicol\u00e1s Lodeiro]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|AM ||'''2''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Clint Dempsey]]\n|-\n|LW ||'''8''' ||{{flagicon|ESP}} [[V\u00edctor Rodr\u00edguez (Spanish footballer)|V\u00edctor Rodr\u00edguez]] || || {{suboff|71}}\n|-\n|CF ||'''17'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Will Bruin]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Tyler Miller (soccer)|Tyler Miller]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|CMR}} [[Nouhou Tolo]] || || {{subon|90+1}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|MEX}} [[Tony Alfaro]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Harry Shipp]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''21'''||{{flagicon|MTQ}} [[Jordy Delem]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''13'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jordan Morris]] || || {{subon|71}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''27'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Lamar Neagle]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Schmetzer]]\n|}\n|}\n\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player'''\n<br />[[Jozy Altidore]] (Toronto FC)\n\n'''[[Assistant referee (association football)|Assistant referees]]'''\n<br />Adam Wienckowski ([[United States Soccer Federation|United States]])\n<br />Jeremy Hanson ([[United States Soccer Federation|United States]])\n<br />'''[[Assistant referee (association football)#Fourth official|Fourth official]]'''\n<br />[[Kevin Stott]] ([[United States Soccer Federation|United States]])\n<br />'''[[Assistant referee (association football)#Fifth official|Fifth official]]'''\n<br />Danny Thornberry\n<br />'''[[Video assistant referee]]'''\n<br />[[David Gantar]] ([[Canadian Soccer Association|Canada]])\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top;\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes.\n*30 minutes of [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]] if necessary.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still level.\n*Seven named substitutes.\n*Maximum of three substitutions, with a fourth allowed in extra time.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nToronto FC became the first Canadian team to win the MLS Cup, and the first MLS team to complete a domestic [[treble (association football)|treble]], after winning the [[Canadian Championship]] and [[Supporters' Shield]] earlier in the season.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 9, 2017 |title=Toronto beats Seattle to win MLS Cup |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42282402 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=December 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213204714/http://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42282402 |archive-date=December 13, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Toronto received a $275,000 USD cash prize as winners, while Seattle was awarded $80,000.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |date=December 9, 2017 |title=MLS Cup win worth $275,000 in bonus cash for TFC |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/12/09/mls-cup-win-worth-275000-in-bonus-cash-for-tfc.html |work=Toronto Star |agency=The Canadian Press |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214124814/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/12/09/mls-cup-win-worth-275000-in-bonus-cash-for-tfc.html |archive-date=December 14, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Due to Toronto's win, the [[2019 CONCACAF Champions League]] berth reserved for the MLS Cup champions will instead go to the US based team (excluding other qualifiers) that finishes with the highest aggregate regular season points in 2017 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stejskal |first=Sam |date=September 22, 2017 |title=How CONCACAF Champions League qualifiers are determined in MLS |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/09/22/how-concacaf-champions-league-qualifiers-are-determined-mls |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026000625/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/09/22/how-concacaf-champions-league-qualifiers-are-determined-mls |archive-date=October 26, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Toronto was ineligible to qualify through the berth, which belongs to the [[United States Soccer Federation]], but qualified for the [[2018 CONCACAF Champions League]] after winning the 2017 Canadian Championship.<ref>{{cite news |last=Straus |first=Brian |date=April 6, 2017 |title=MLS clubs have resolution over qualifying for future CCL after format change |url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2017/04/06/concacaf-champions-league-ccl-qualifying-format-changes |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=December 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021071042/https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2017/04/06/concacaf-champions-league-ccl-qualifying-format-changes |archive-date=October 21, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Molinaro |first=John |date=July 24, 2017 |title=Champions League ambitions a sign of culture change at TFC |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/tfc-toronto-fc-bill-manning-concacaf-champions-league-mls-major-league-soccer/ |publisher=Sportsnet |accessdate=December 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210123736/http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/tfc-toronto-fc-bill-manning-concacaf-champions-league-mls-major-league-soccer/ |archive-date=December 10, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Toronto was also qualified to host and play in the inaugural [[2018 Campeones Cup|Campeones Cup]], a new competition staged between the winners of the MLS Cup and the Mexican [[Campe\u00f3n de Campeones]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Peterson |first=Anne M. |date=13 March 2018 |title=Toronto FC to host first Campeones Cup as MLS, Mexico's Liga MX form partnership |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2018/03/13/toronto-fc-to-host-first-campeones-cup-as-mls-mexicos-liga-mx-form-partnership.html |agency=Associated Press |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=November 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626030815/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2018/03/13/toronto-fc-to-host-first-campeones-cup-as-mls-mexicos-liga-mx-form-partnership.html |archive-date=June 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Toronto played against [[Tigres UANL]] on September 19, 2018, and lost 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shoalts |first=David |date=September 19, 2018 |title=Mexico's Tigres get a little payback, defeat Toronto FC in Campeones Cup |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/article-mexicos-tigres-get-a-little-payback-defeat-toronto-fc-in-campeones/ |work=The Globe and Mail |accessdate=November 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109081517/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/article-mexicos-tigres-get-a-little-payback-defeat-toronto-fc-in-campeones/ |archive-date=November 9, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe day after the final, ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' mistakenly ran pre-scheduled advertisements on its website that promoted a victory parade and rally for the Sounders, which were later removed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Alexandra |date=December 11, 2017 |title=Seattle paper shows MLS \u2018victory\u2019 ads for Sounders |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/12/11/seattle-paper-shows-mls-victory-ads-for-sounders.html |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213162326/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/12/11/seattle-paper-shows-mls-victory-ads-for-sounders.html |archive-date=December 13, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> As part of a pre-match wager between the mayors of the two cities, [[Seattle City Hall]] was lit in red on December 13.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 13, 2017 |title=Seattle City Hall illuminated in red to honor mayor's MLS Cup friendly bet with Toronto |url=http://komonews.com/news/local/seattle-city-hall-illuminated-in-red-to-honor-mayors-mls-cup-friendly-bet-with-toronto |publisher=[[KOMO-TV|KOMO 4 News]] |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214071116/http://komonews.com/news/local/seattle-city-hall-illuminated-in-red-to-honor-mayors-mls-cup-friendly-bet-with-toronto |archive-date=December 14, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Toronto FC celebrated their victory with a parade two days after the final on December 11, traveling from [[Maple Leaf Square]] to [[Nathan Phillips Square]] in downtown Toronto. The parade was attended by a several thousand fans, as well as Toronto Mayor [[John Tory]], who declared the day as \"Reds Day\".<ref>{{cite news |date=December 11, 2017 |title=Toronto FC victory parade, fan rally take over downtown |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/toronto-fc-champion-parade-route-rally-1.4442569 |work=[[CBC News]] |accessdate=December 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212000809/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/toronto-fc-champion-parade-route-rally-1.4442569 |archive-date=December 12, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It was the second victory parade held in the city in as many weeks, as the [[Toronto Argonauts]] had won the [[Canadian Football League]]'s [[Grey Cup]] in November.<ref>{{cite news |last=McKenna |first=Ryan |date=December 11, 2017 |title=Chanting fans pack downtown Toronto to celebrate TFC's MLS Cup championship |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/sports-pmn/toronto-fc-to-hold-downtown-victory-parade-following-mls-cup-championship |work=The National Post |agency=The Canadian Press |accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Association football|Ontario}}\n{{MLSCup}}\n{{2017 in American soccer}}\n{{2017 in Canadian soccer}}\n{{Seattle Sounders FC matches}}\n{{Toronto FC matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mls Cup 2017}}\n[[Category:MLS Cup|2017]]\n[[Category:2017 Major League Soccer season]]\n[[Category:Toronto FC matches]]\n[[Category:Seattle Sounders FC matches]]\n[[Category:2017 in Ontario|MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:2010s in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Soccer in Toronto]]\n[[Category:December 2017 sports events in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{redirect|2017 MLS Cup|details on the tournament|2017 MLS Cup Playoffs}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title      = MLS Cup 2017\n| image      = Bmo Field 2016 East Stand.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = [[BMO Field]] in [[Toronto]] hosted the match\n| event      = [[MLS Cup]]\n| team1      = [[Toronto FC]]\n| team1score = 2\n| team2      = [[Seattle Sounders FC]]\n| team2score = 0\n| details    =\n| date       = {{Start date|2017|12|9}}\n| stadium    = [[BMO Field]]\n| city       = [[Toronto]], Canada\n| man_of_the_match1aname = [[MLS Cup#Most valuable player|MLS Cup MVP]]\n| man_of_the_match1a = [[Jozy Altidore]]<br />{{nowrap|(Toronto FC)}}\n| referee    = [[Allen Chapman]]<ref name=\"PRORef\">{{cite web |date=December 2, 2017 |title=2017 MLS Cup crew announced |url=http://proreferees.com/2017/12/02/2017-mls-cup-crew-announced/ |publisher=[[Professional Referee Organization]] |accessdate=December 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203224623/http://proreferees.com/2017/12/02/2017-mls-cup-crew-announced/ |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| attendance = 30,584\n| weather    = Cloudy<br />{{convert|1|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}<br />56% [[humidity]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/CYTZ/2017/12/9/DailyHistory.html |title=Weather History for Toronto, Canada |website=[[Weather Underground (weather service)|Weather Underground]] |publisher=[[The Weather Company]] |date=December 9, 2017 |access-date=June 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140644/https://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/CYTZ/2017/12/9/DailyHistory.html |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| previous   = [[MLS Cup 2016|2016]]\n| next       = [[MLS Cup 2018|2018]]\n}}\n'''MLS Cup 2017''' was the 22nd edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), contested between [[Toronto FC]] and [[Seattle Sounders FC]] on December 9, 2017. The match was hosted at [[BMO Field]] in [[Toronto]], Canada, for the second consecutive year and third time overall. Both teams made their second appearance in the MLS Cup, in a rematch of the [[MLS Cup 2016|2016 edition]].\n\nAfter a goalless first half, Toronto FC took the lead in the 67th minute through a [[Jozy Altidore]] goal. Toronto's 2\u20130 win over Seattle was capped by a 94th minute counterattack that resulted in a goal by [[V\u00edctor V\u00e1zquez Solsona|V\u00edctor V\u00e1zquez]]. Toronto FC became the first Canadian team to win the MLS Cup and the first MLS team to complete a [[Treble (association football)|domestic treble]].\n\nDue to Toronto's win, the [[2019 CONCACAF Champions League]] berth reserved for the MLS Cup champions instead went to [[New York Red Bulls]], the US based team (excluding other qualifiers) that finished with the highest aggregate regular season points in 2017 and 2018. Toronto was ineligible to qualify through the berth, which belongs to the [[United States Soccer Federation]], but participated in the [[2018 CONCACAF Champions League]] after winning the Canadian Championship. Toronto also qualified to host and play in the inaugural [[2018 Campeones Cup|Campeones Cup]] against [[2018 Campe\u00f3n de Campeones|Campe\u00f3n de Campeones]] winners [[Tigres UANL]].\n\n==Road to the final==\n{{details|2017 MLS Cup Playoffs}}\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club soccer league in the United States and Canada. The [[2017 Major League Soccer season|2017 season]] was the 22nd in MLS history, and was contested by 22 teams in two conferences in the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|east]] and [[Western Conference (MLS)|west]]. Each club played 34 matches during the regular season from March to October, facing each team in the same conference at least twice and teams in the other conference at least once.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 11, 2017 |title=MLS releases 2017 regular season schedule |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/schedule/2017/announcement |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=November 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511053403/https://www.mlssoccer.com/schedule/2017/announcement |archive-date=May 11, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=January 12, 2017 |title=Major League Soccer releases full 2017 regular-season schedule |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/major-league-soccer-releases-full-2017-regular-season-schedule/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=November 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040907/https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/major-league-soccer-releases-full-2017-regular-season-schedule/ |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The playoffs, running from October to December, were contested between the top six clubs in each conference and included four rounds: a one-match knockout round for the lowest-seeded teams, two rounds of home-and-away series, and the one-match final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goldberg |first=Jamie |date=October 24, 2017 |title=A guide to the 2017 MLS Cup Playoffs: Teams, dates, seeding, format |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/timbers/index.ssf/2017/10/a_guide_to_the_2017_mls_cup_pl.html |work=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=November 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033302/http://www.oregonlive.com/timbers/index.ssf/2017/10/a_guide_to_the_2017_mls_cup_pl.html |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe two finalists, Toronto and Seattle, faced each other in the [[MLS Cup 2016|2016 cup]], which was won by Seattle in a penalty shootout.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 1, 2017 |title=Sounders return to MLS Cup after 3-0 rout of Dynamo |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/sounders-return-to-mls-cup-after-3-0-rout-of-dynamo/ |work=[[CBS Sports]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=December 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230060305/https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/sounders-return-to-mls-cup-after-3-0-rout-of-dynamo/ |archive-date=December 30, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It was the third in league history to feature a rematch of the previous year, the other two being the 2006 and 2007 wins by [[Houston Dynamo]] and the 2011 and 2012 wins by [[LA Galaxy]].<ref>{{cite news |date=December 1, 2017 |title=2017 MLS Cup: Seattle visit Toronto for third Cup rematch in MLS history |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/12/01/2017-mls-cup-sees-rematch-seattle-sounders-toronto-fc |publisher=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202170003/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/12/01/2017-mls-cup-sees-rematch-seattle-sounders-toronto-fc |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The 2017 cup was also the first to see both of the higher-seeded sides advance from the conference finals since it was changed to a [[two-legged tie|home-and-away series]], in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last=Quillen |first=Ian |date=November 21, 2017 |title=History suggests there won't be a 2016 MLS Cup rematch this year |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/11/21/history-suggests-there-wont-be-2016-mls-cup-rematch-year |publisher=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=November 30, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121223217/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/11/21/history-suggests-there-wont-be-2016-mls-cup-rematch-year |archive-date=November 21, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The two teams played a single regular season match, hosted by Seattle in May, which Toronto won 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=May 6, 2017 |title=Sounders lose MLS Cup rematch 1-0 at home to Toronto FC |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-lose-mls-cup-rematch-1-0-at-home-to-toronto-fc/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=November 30, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201132212/https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-lose-mls-cup-rematch-1-0-at-home-to-toronto-fc/ |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Toronto FC===\n{{further|2017 Toronto FC season}}\n[[File:Giovinco 230515.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|[[Sebastian Giovinco]] lead Toronto FC in goals scored during their treble campaign in 2017]]\n\nAfter their MLS Cup loss, Toronto FC looked to return to the cup as well as compete for the [[Supporters' Shield]] and [[Canadian Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Armstrong |first=Laura |date=March 28, 2017 |title=Fans, TFC players have a growing bond |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/03/28/fans-tfc-players-have-a-growing-bond.html |work=[[Toronto Star]] |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202052616/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/03/28/fans-tfc-players-have-a-growing-bond.html |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |date=February 24, 2017 |title=TFC looking to avenge Major League Soccer Cup loss |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/02/24/tfc-looking-to-avenge-major-league-soccer-cup-loss.html |work=Toronto Star |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202052520/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/02/24/tfc-looking-to-avenge-major-league-soccer-cup-loss.html |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In addition to their 2016 roster, the team acquired French leftback [[Chris Mavinga]] and Spanish midfielder [[V\u00edctor V\u00e1zquez Solsona|V\u00edctor V\u00e1zquez]] to fill depth roles;<ref>{{cite news |last=Boehm |first=Charles |date=February 27, 2017 |title=2017 Season Preview: Toronto FC |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/02/27/toronto-fc-2017-team-guide |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201182903/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/02/27/toronto-fc-2017-team-guide |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> manager [[Greg Vanney]] placed a strong emphasis on an organized defense, one of the team's strengths during the 2016 season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Molinaro |first=John |date=January 27, 2017 |title=Defence to remain a guiding principle for Toronto FC in 2017 |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/tfc-toronto-fc-mls-major-league-soccer-greg-vanney-clint-irwin-drew-moor/ |work=[[Sportsnet]] |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202052828/http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/tfc-toronto-fc-mls-major-league-soccer-greg-vanney-clint-irwin-drew-moor/ |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The team entered the season as a favorite to win the cup,<ref>{{cite news |last=Goldberg |first=Jamie |date=March 1, 2017 |title=New York Red Bulls, Toronto FC early favorites to win 2017 MLS Cup: Complete odds |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/timbers/index.ssf/2017/03/new_york_red_bulls_toronto_fc.html |work=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201232731/http://www.oregonlive.com/timbers/index.ssf/2017/03/new_york_red_bulls_toronto_fc.html |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> as well as a key challenger for the Supporters' Shield.<ref>{{cite news |last=Platt |first=Oliver |date=March 1, 2017 |title=Toronto FC is the team to beat in MLS this season |url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2017/3/1/14757520/mls-preview-2017-tfc-toronto-fc |work=[[SB Nation]] |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201233117/https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2017/3/1/14757520/mls-preview-2017-tfc-toronto-fc |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Toronto immediately jumped into a run of good form, with only three losses in the first half of the season, and remained near level with [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] at the top of the league.<ref>{{cite news |last=Molinaro |first=John |date=July 1, 2017 |title=It was just one of those nights for TFC in Dallas |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/tfc-toronto-fc-fc-dallas-mls-major-league-soccer/ |work=Sportsnet |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202052817/http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/tfc-toronto-fc-fc-dallas-mls-major-league-soccer/ |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Despite two consecutive losses in September, Toronto finished the season as Supporters' Shield champion, breaking the record for most points (69) and tying the record for most wins (20).<ref>{{cite news |date=October 27, 2017 |title=MLS Preview: Sounders begin title defense without Dempsey |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/90minutes/ct-hoy-mls-preview-sounders-begin-title-defense-without-dempsey-20171027-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202000020/http://www.chicagotribune.com/90minutes/ct-hoy-mls-preview-sounders-begin-title-defense-without-dempsey-20171027-story.html |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 22, 2017 |title=Toronto FC breaks MLS season points record held by 1998 Galaxy |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/toronto-fc/story/3236257/toronto-fc-breaks-mls-season-points-record-held-by-1998-galaxy |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202052504/http://www.espn.com/soccer/toronto-fc/story/3236257/toronto-fc-breaks-mls-season-points-record-held-by-1998-galaxy |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nToronto faced the [[New York Red Bulls]] in the conference semifinals and took a 2\u20131 lead away in New Jersey. The team returned home and lost 1\u20130, but advanced on the [[away goals rule]] with the 2\u20132 aggregate draw.<ref>{{cite news |last=Molinaro |first=John |date=November 5, 2017 |title=Toronto FC falls to Red Bulls, still reaches East Final on aggregate |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/toronto-fc-falls-red-bulls-still-reaches-east-final-aggregate/ |work=Sportsnet |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207042247/http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/toronto-fc-falls-red-bulls-still-reaches-east-final-aggregate/ |archive-date=December 7, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The home fixture was marred by a halftime brawl between the teams that saw [[Jozy Altidore]] sent off and [[Sebastian Giovinco]] suspended for yellow card accumulation in receiving a yellow card in two consecutive matches.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |date=November 17, 2017 |title=TFC's Jozy Altidore avoids longer suspension over halftime tunnel fight with Red Bulls players |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/11/17/tfcs-jozy-altidore-avoids-longer-suspension-over-halftime-tunnel-fight-with-red-bulls-players.html |work=Toronto Star |agency=The Canadian Press |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201232723/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/11/17/tfcs-jozy-altidore-avoids-longer-suspension-over-halftime-tunnel-fight-with-red-bulls-players.html |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In the conference finals, Toronto traveled to play [[Columbus Crew SC]], earning a 0\u20130 away draw and a 1\u20130 win at home, qualifying them for the MLS Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |date=November 29, 2017 |title=Toronto FC to host MLS final after 1-0 win over Columbus in eastern final |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3888759/toronto-fc-to-host-mls-final-after-1-0-win-over-columbus-in-eastern-final/ |work=[[Global News]] |agency=The Canadian Press |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130043407/https://globalnews.ca/news/3888759/toronto-fc-to-host-mls-final-after-1-0-win-over-columbus-in-eastern-final/ |archive-date=November 30, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Seattle Sounders FC===\n{{further|2017 Seattle Sounders FC season}}\n\nThe Sounders entered the season as defending MLS Cup champions, their first title after years of early playoff exits.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=December 9, 2016 |title=In MLS Cup, Toronto FC and Seattle Sounders embrace cold weather and hot expectations |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2016/12/09/in-mls-cup-toronto-fc-and-seattle-sounders-embrace-cold-weather-and-hot-expectations/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808074907/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2016/12/09/in-mls-cup-toronto-fc-and-seattle-sounders-embrace-cold-weather-and-hot-expectations/ |archive-date=August 8, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Head coach [[Brian Schmetzer]], promoted from his interim role, made offseason roster changes to replace older veteran players with younger talent that align with general manager [[Garth Lagerwey]]'s vision for the club.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=February 21, 2017 |title=Best in the West? Sounders' new challenge is marathon, not sprint |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/us/features/seattle-sounders-2017-mls-preview |work=[[FourFourTwo]] |accessdate=December 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203224455/https://www.fourfourtwo.com/us/features/seattle-sounders-2017-mls-preview |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=January 24, 2017 |title=Nelson Valdez, Andreas Ivanschitz, Erik Friberg, Tyrone Mears among Sounders with contract options declined for 2017 |page=C4 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/nelson-valdez-andreas-ivanschitz-erik-friberg-tyrone-mears-among-sounders-with-contract-options-declined-for-2017/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930222706/https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/nelson-valdez-andreas-ivanschitz-erik-friberg-tyrone-mears-among-sounders-with-contract-options-declined-for-2017/ |archive-date=September 30, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Among the additions were MLS veteran [[Will Bruin]], [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|homegrown player]] [[Henry Wingo]], academy graduate [[Nouhou Tolo]], and veteran defenders [[Gustav Svensson]] and [[Kelvin Leerdam]], adding to the team's depth positions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Miles |first=Todd |date=December 1, 2017 |title=3 biggest reasons the Sounders are back in the MLS Cup |url=http://www.thenewstribune.com/sports/soccer/mls/sounders-fc/article187641083.html |work=[[The News Tribune]] |location=Tacoma, Washington |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206005918/http://www.thenewstribune.com/sports/soccer/mls/sounders-fc/article187641083.html |archive-date=December 6, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=March 25, 2017 |title=Sounders give extended look to several non-starters in 'friendly' against Club Necaxa |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-give-extended-look-to-several-non-starters-in-friendly-against-club-necaxa/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202053534/https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-give-extended-look-to-several-non-starters-in-friendly-against-club-necaxa/ |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Seattle started the season slowly, with only five wins in the first 17 matches, due to injury troubles and inconsistent lineups.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=August 11, 2017 |title=Sounders enter first-place showdown with Sporting KC healthy and riding 7-game unbeaten streak |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-head-in-to-first-place-showdown-confident-in-team-theyve-shaped/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202053436/https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-head-in-to-first-place-showdown-confident-in-team-theyve-shaped/ |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> From late June to early September, the team welcomed back injured players and went on a 13-match unbeaten streak that put them in playoff contention.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Brennan |date=September 23, 2017 |title=Sounders' 13-match unbeaten streak comes to end with 2-0 loss to Real Salt Lake |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-13-match-unbeaten-streak-comes-to-end-with-2-0-loss-to-real-salt-lake/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202053342/https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-13-match-unbeaten-streak-comes-to-end-with-2-0-loss-to-real-salt-lake/ |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The streak ended with a series of draws and losses,<ref>{{cite news |last=Pentz |first=Matt |date=September 27, 2017 |title=Sounders romp over first-place Vancouver for first win in a month, move into tie for 2nd in West |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-crush-vancouver-move-into-2nd-in-west/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202053413/https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/sounders-crush-vancouver-move-into-2nd-in-west/ |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> but the Sounders recovered with three wins in late September and October to clinch a second-place finish in the Western Conference.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 22, 2017 |title=Defending MLS champion Seattle Sounders claim No. 2 playoff seed in West |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mls/2017/10/22/nicolas-lodeiro-scores-twice-sounders-beat-rapids/106919348/ |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202111248/https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mls/2017/10/22/nicolas-lodeiro-scores-twice-sounders-beat-rapids/106919348/ |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nSeattle faced their Canadian rivals, the [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]], in the conference semifinals. After a scoreless draw in Vancouver, the Sounders returned home and won 2\u20130 on a pair of goals scored by [[Clint Dempsey]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Calkins |first=Matt |date=November 2, 2017 |title=Clint Dempsey rises to the occasion with clutch goals for Sounders in playoff win over Vancouver |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/clint-dempsey-rises-to-the-occasion-for-sounders/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202053403/https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/clint-dempsey-rises-to-the-occasion-for-sounders/ |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In the conference finals, the Sounders played [[Houston Dynamo]] and earned a 2\u20130 win in the away leg after a Dynamo player was sent off early in the match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Roepken |first=Corey |date=November 22, 2017 |title=Sounders beat Dynamo 2-0 in first leg of West final |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/sports/dynamo/article/Sounders-beat-Dynamo-2-0-in-first-leg-of-West-12376360.php |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202052916/http://www.houstonchronicle.com/sports/dynamo/article/Sounders-beat-Dynamo-2-0-in-first-leg-of-West-12376360.php |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Heading into the home leg with an advantage on away goals, Seattle went for an aggressive 3\u20130 win to give them a 5\u20130 aggregate win that was capped by home-and-away goals by former Dynamo forward [[Will Bruin]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Bell |first=Arch |date=December 1, 2017 |title=Inconsistencies in attack and the lineup prove to be Houston's downfall |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/club/houston-dynamo/6077/blog/post/3293022/inconsistencies-in-attack-and-the-lineup-prove-to-be-houstons-downfall |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201215524/http://www.espn.com/soccer/club/houston-dynamo/6077/blog/post/3293022/inconsistencies-in-attack-and-the-lineup-prove-to-be-houstons-downfall |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Sounders maintained a shutout streak that carried over from the 2016 Western Conference Final, reaching 647 minutes after the win over Houston.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wahl |first=Grant |date=November 30, 2017 |title=Sounders Finish Off Dynamo to Set Up MLS Cup Rematch vs. Toronto FC |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2017/11/30/seattle-sounders-houston-dynamo-western-conference-final-second-leg-mls-cup-toronto |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=December 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202102726/https://www.si.com/soccer/2017/11/30/seattle-sounders-houston-dynamo-western-conference-final-second-leg-mls-cup-toronto |archive-date=December 2, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away).''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[Toronto FC]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[Seattle Sounders FC]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top|1st place in [[2017 Major League Soccer season#Eastern Conference|Eastern Conference]]\n{{2017 Major League Soccer Eastern Conference table|only_pld_pts=yes|showteam=TOR|show_limit=5}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2017 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|2nd place in [[2017 Major League Soccer season#Western Conference|Western Conference]]\n{{2017 Major League Soccer Western Conference table|only_pld_pts=yes|showteam=SEA|show_limit=5}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|[[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[New York Red Bulls]]\n|2\u20132 ([[Away goals rule|a]])\n|[[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#New York Red Bulls v Toronto FC|2\u20131]] (A)\n|[[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#Toronto FC v New York Red Bulls|0\u20131]] (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]]\n|2\u20130\n|[[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#Vancouver Whitecaps v Seattle Sounders|0\u20130]] (A)\n|[[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#Seattle Sounders v Vancouver Whitecaps|2\u20130]] (H)\n|-\n|align=left|[[Columbus Crew SC]]\n|1\u20130\n|[[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#Columbus Crew v Toronto FC|0\u20130]] (A)\n|[[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#Toronto FC v Columbus Crew|1\u20130]] (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Finals\n|align=left|[[Houston Dynamo]]\n|5\u20130\n|[[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#Houston Dynamo v Seattle Sounders|2\u20130]] (A)\n|[[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#Seattle Sounders v Houston Dynamo|3\u20130]] (H)\n|}\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:BMO Field in 2016.png|thumb|right|[[BMO Field]] hosted the MLS Cup final for a third time]]\n\n[[BMO Field]] was confirmed as the host of MLS Cup 2017 after [[Toronto FC]] won the Eastern Conference Championship on November 29, 2017, leaving them as the highest remaining seed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 29, 2017 |title=Tonight, the first MLS Cup finalist will be decided \u2014 and the site of MLS Cup |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2017/11/29/tonight-the-first-mls-cup-finalist-will-be-decided-and-the-site-of-mls-cup/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=November 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129220819/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2017/11/29/tonight-the-first-mls-cup-finalist-will-be-decided-and-the-site-of-mls-cup/ |archive-date=November 29, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The stadium was renovated and expanded prior to the 2016 season and hosted [[MLS Cup 2016]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Larson |first=Kurtis |date=May 5, 2016 |title='A whole new stadium': Take a look at renovated BMO Field ahead of Toronto FC home opener |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/sports/soccer/a-whole-new-stadium-take-a-look-at-renovated-bmo-field-ahead-of-toronto-fc-home-opener |work=[[National Post]] |accessdate=November 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20160509232812/http://news.nationalpost.com/sports/soccer/a-whole-new-stadium-take-a-look-at-renovated-bmo-field-ahead-of-toronto-fc-home-opener |archive-date=May 9, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Keating |first=Steve |date=December 10, 2016 |title=Sounders beat Toronto FC on penalties to win MLS Cup |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-usa-mlscup/sounders-beat-toronto-fc-on-penalties-to-win-mls-cup-idUSKBN140043 |work=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=November 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043233/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-usa-mlscup/sounders-beat-toronto-fc-on-penalties-to-win-mls-cup-idUSKBN140043 |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Capacity for the 2017 cup was the standard capacity of BMO Field at about 30,000 seats, compared to the extra 6,000 seats available at the 2016 cup which had been reused after a temporary installation for the [[104th Grey Cup|Grey Cup]] and [[NHL Centennial Classic]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Armstrong |first=Laura |date=November 29, 2016 |title=TFC knows the score, and 1-0 would be just fine |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2016/11/29/toronto-fc-clash-with-montreal-sets-bmo-field-record.html |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=December 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220053419/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2016/11/29/toronto-fc-clash-with-montreal-sets-bmo-field-record.html |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn December 1, a round of tickets was released to season seat holders and quickly sold out. Additional tickets were released to the general public on December 4, which were sold out in less than an hour and appeared on secondary markets for well above face value shortly after.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ngabo |first=Gilbert |date=December 5, 2017 |title=BMO Field sold out again for Toronto FC finals game |url=http://www.metronews.ca/news/toronto/2017/12/05/bmo-field-sold-out-again-for-toronto-fc-finals-game.html |work=[[StarMetro (newspaper)|Metro]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313090603/http://www.metronews.ca/news/toronto/2017/12/05/bmo-field-sold-out-again-for-toronto-fc-finals-game.html |archivedate=March 13, 2018 |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe MLS Cup final was broadcast in English by [[ESPN]] in the United States and [[The Sports Network|TSN]] in Canada. [[UniM\u00e1s]] and [[Univision Deportes]] carried the Spanish broadcast in the United States, while [[TVA Sports]] carried the French broadcast in Canada.<ref>{{cite press release |date=August 23, 2017 |title=2017 MLS Cup set for December 9, live on ESPN, UniM\u00e1s, TSN and TVA Sports |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/08/23/2017-mls-cup-set-december-9-live-espn-unim-s-tsn-and-tva-sports |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=November 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003224003/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/08/23/2017-mls-cup-set-december-9-live-espn-unim-s-tsn-and-tva-sports |archive-date=October 3, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFor ESPN, [[Adrian Healey]], [[Taylor Twellman]], and [[Julie Stewart-Binks]] called the match, with pre-game and post-game coverage conducted by [[Max Bretos]], [[Kasey Keller]], and [[Alejandro Moreno]].<ref>{{cite press release |date=December 7, 2017 |title=ESPN Presents 2017 MLS Cup |url=http://espnmediazone.com/us/press-releases/2017/12/espn-presents-2017-mls-cup/ |work=ESPN MediaZone |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=December 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102103/http://espnmediazone.com/us/press-releases/2017/12/espn-presents-2017-mls-cup/ |archive-date=December 23, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |last=Nwulu |first=Mac |date=December 4, 2017 |title=ESPN/ESPN2 Audience for 2017 MLS Cup Playoffs Up 38 Percent |url=http://espnmediazone.com/us/press-releases/2017/12/espnespn2-audience-2017-mls-cup-playoffs-38-percent/ |work=ESPN MediaZone |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205052823/http://espnmediazone.com/us/press-releases/2017/12/espnespn2-audience-2017-mls-cup-playoffs-38-percent/ |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> For TSN, Luke Wileman and [[Steven Caldwell]] called the match, with pre-game and post-game coverage conducted by [[James Duthie (sportscaster)|James Duthie]], alongside Terry Dunfield and Kristian Jack.<ref>{{cite press release |date=December 7, 2017 |title=Toronto FC Chases MLS CUP Redemption, Live this Saturday (Dec. 9) at 3:30 p.m. ET on TSN |url=http://www.bellmedia.ca/pr/press/toronto-fc-chases-mls-cup-redemption-live-this-saturday-dec-9-at-330-p-m-et-on-tsn/ |publisher=[[Bell Media]] |accessdate=December 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223102351/http://www.bellmedia.ca/pr/press/toronto-fc-chases-mls-cup-redemption-live-this-saturday-dec-9-at-330-p-m-et-on-tsn/ |archive-date=December 23, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> For UniM\u00e1s and Univision Deportes, Raul Guzm\u00e1n, [[Marcelo Balboa]], and Diego Balado called the match.<ref>{{cite press release |date=December 7, 2017 |title=Univision Deportes to Broadcast 2017 MLS Cup |url=https://corporate.univision.com/corporate/press/2017/12/07/univision-deportes-broadcast-2017-mls-cup/ |publisher=[[Univision Communications]] |accessdate=December 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223160555/https://corporate.univision.com/corporate/press/2017/12/07/univision-deportes-broadcast-2017-mls-cup/ |archive-date=December 23, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Viewership and ratings===\nThe ESPN broadcast registered a 0.7 [[Nielsen rating]], up 75 percent from the [[MLS Cup 2015]] broadcast on ESPN.<ref>{{cite news |last=Boehm |first=Charles |date=December 10, 2017 |title=MLS Cup 2017 television ratings on ESPN rise 75 percent over 2015 edition |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/12/10/mls-cup-2017-television-ratings-espn-rise-75-percent-over-2015-edition |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref> The ESPN and Spanish language broadcasts in the United States drew an audience of 1.1 million combined viewers, a 43 percent decline from the 2016 final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://worldsoccertalk.com/2017/12/12/2017-mls-cup-final-viewership-drops-43-across-espn-univision-deportes/ |title=2017 MLS Cup final viewership drops 43% across ESPN and Univision Deportes |publisher=World Soccer Talk |first=Christopher |last=Harris |date=December 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222220206/http://worldsoccertalk.com/2017/12/12/2017-mls-cup-final-viewership-drops-43-across-espn-univision-deportes/ |archive-date=December 22, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The TSN broadcast drew an audience of 1.3 million viewers in Canada, a 13.3 percent decline from the 2016 final.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 11, 2017 |title=MLS Cup rematch between Toronto and Seattle sees ratings dip in Canada |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/sports-pmn/mls-cup-rematch-between-toronto-and-seattle-sees-ratings-dip-in-canada |work=[[The National Post]] |agency=The Canadian Press |accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:Stefan Frei 2.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.8|Seattle's [[Stefan Frei]] made six saves in the first half, tying an MLS Cup record set in 2003]]\n\nDespite forecasts with cold and snowy conditions,<ref>{{cite news |last=Bondy |first=Filip |date=December 7, 2017 |title=MLS Cup Caught Between A Rock And A Cold Place |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/filipbondy/2017/12/07/mls-cup-caught-between-a-rock-and-a-cold-place/#70e0104d4cf3 |work=Forbes |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214125219/https://www.forbes.com/sites/filipbondy/2017/12/07/mls-cup-caught-between-a-rock-and-a-cold-place/#70e0104d4cf3 |archive-date=December 14, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> the match kicked off in cloudy weather at a temperature of {{convert|1|C|F}}, reported to be {{convert|-7|C|F}} with [[wind chill]].<ref name=\"Guardian-Live\">{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Bob |date=December 9, 2017 |title=Toronto FC defeat Seattle Sounders to win the MLS Cup \u2013 as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2017/dec/09/mls-cup-final-toronto-fc-v-seattle-sounders- |work=The Guardian |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213110554/https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2017/dec/09/mls-cup-final-toronto-fc-v-seattle-sounders- |archive-date=December 13, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Sounders were without injured captain [[Osvaldo Alonso]],<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite news |last=Petterson |first=Joel |date=December 10, 2017 |title=Toronto F.C. Wins M.L.S. Cup, and a Little Redemption |page=SP2 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/09/sports/soccer/mls-cup-toronto-altidore.html?_r=0 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214124741/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/09/sports/soccer/mls-cup-toronto-altidore.html?_r=0 |archive-date=December 14, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and also chose to start Joevin Jones at left back in place of Nouhou Tolo.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |date=December 9, 2017 |title=Joevin Jones to start at left back in final game of Sounders career as club goes with veteran lineup |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/joevin-jones-to-start-at-left-back-in-final-game-of-sounders-career-as-club-goes-with-veteran-lineup/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214125114/https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/sounders/joevin-jones-to-start-at-left-back-in-final-game-of-sounders-career-as-club-goes-with-veteran-lineup/ |archive-date=December 14, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Toronto switched to a 4\u20134\u20132 diamond formation, a departure from the 3\u20135\u20132 formation used during the regular season and playoff, as Greg Vanney attempted to counter Seattle's strong central players.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Graham |date=December 9, 2017 |title=Jozy Altidore has last laugh to seal MLS Cup glory for Toronto FC |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/dec/09/jozy-altidore-mls-cup-glory-toronto-fc-seattle-sounders |work=The Guardian |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213063055/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/dec/09/jozy-altidore-mls-cup-glory-toronto-fc-seattle-sounders |archive-date=December 13, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nToronto spent most of the first half in possession, making several attacking runs and being the more dominant team. They were unable to score, however, due to a series of saves from Seattle's [[Stefan Frei]],<ref name=\"NYTimes\"/> who tied an MLS Cup record for second most saves in a half at six saves, behind [[Pat Onstad]]'s seven at the [[MLS Cup 2003|2003 final]].<ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=December 9, 2017 |title=Le Toronto FC triomphe en finale de la MLS des Sounders de Seattle |language=French |trans-title=Toronto FC triumphs in MLS final over Seattle Sounders |url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1072225/toronto-fc-seattle-sounders-mls-finale-soccer |publisher=[[Radio-Canada]] |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211151322/http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1072225/toronto-fc-seattle-sounders-mls-finale-soccer |archive-date=December 11, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He made a diving stop to deny [[Sebastian Giovinco]] in the 10th minute and a push on the ball from Giovinco in the 23rd minute.<ref name=\"Guardian-Live\"/> Jones took Seattle's first shot of the match in the 30th minute, ending the club's 150-minute streak without a shot on target between the two MLS Cup finals.<ref name=\"Guardian-Live\"/><ref name=\"Guardian\"/> In the final moments of the half, Frei saved a shot from [[V\u00edctor V\u00e1zquez Solsona|V\u00edctor V\u00e1zquez]] and the Sounders nearly scored an [[own goal]] after Joevin Jones made a clearance that veered towards the goal.<ref name=\"Star-Live\">{{cite news |last=Armstrong |first=Laura |date=December 9, 2017 |title=Minute by minute: How TFC won the MLS Cup |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/12/09/minute-by-minute-how-tfc-won-the-mls-cup.html |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214041111/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/12/09/minute-by-minute-how-tfc-won-the-mls-cup.html |archive-date=December 14, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Sounders-Summary\">{{cite news |date=December 9, 2017 |title=Sounders FC falls 2-0 to Toronto FC in 2017 MLS Cup |url=https://www.soundersfc.com/post/2017/12/09/sounders-fc-falls-2-0-toronto-fc-2017-mls-cup |publisher=Seattle Sounders FC |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214125020/https://www.soundersfc.com/post/2017/12/09/sounders-fc-falls-2-0-toronto-fc-2017-mls-cup |archive-date=December 14, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Sounders were largely unable to challenge the Toronto goal, with the exception of several counterattacks through the middle of the field.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/>\n\nToronto continued its control of possession and attacking chances early in the second half, with Frei making two key saves on shots from [[Michael Bradley (soccer)|Michael Bradley]] and Giovinco after the hour mark.<ref name=\"Guardian-Live\"/> In the 67th minute, Toronto strung together a series of passes on a counterattack to [[Jozy Altidore]], who finished with a left-footed shot over Frei to open the scoring.<ref name=\"Star-Live\"/> Seattle brought on [[Jordan Morris]] for [[V\u00edctor Rodr\u00edguez (Spanish footballer)|V\u00edctor Rodr\u00edguez]], and he immediately tried a shot towards Toronto's goal that was wide of the post.<ref name=\"BBC-Live\">{{cite news |last=Whalley |first=Mike |date=December 9, 2017 |title=MLS Cup final - Toronto defeat Seattle 2-0 - Live |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/42282192 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=December 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212060455/http://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/42282192 |archive-date=December 12, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> During a corner kick for the Sounders in the 83rd minute, a wire holding the [[Skycam]] system over the stadium fell onto the pitch, causing a short delay.<ref name=\"BBC-Live\"/> Toronto made two consecutive substitutions, switching [[Armando Cooper]] for [[Jonathan Osorio]] at midfield and Altidore for centerback [[Nick Hagglund]]. Seattle attempted to score an equalizer, taking shots that forced Toronto goalkeeper [[Alex Bono]] to save, but were unable to prevent Toronto from counterattacking. In the 90th minute, Giovinco fell from a shoulder challenge from [[Cristian Roldan]] in the penalty area, but calls for a penalty were denied by referee [[Allen Chapman]].<ref name=\"BBC-Live\"/> Both teams made their final substitutions early in stoppage time, with Toronto bringing on [[Beno\u00eet Cheyrou]] for [[Marky Delgado]] and Seattle switching Jones with Nouhou.<ref name=\"Guardian-Live\"/> A Toronto counterattack in the 94th minute ended with a shot from Cooper that hit the post, but the rebound was finished by V\u00e1zquez, clinching a 2\u20130 victory.<ref name=\"BBC-Live\"/>\n\n===Details===\n<onlyinclude>{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2017|12|9}}\n|time       = 4:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|team1      = [[Toronto FC]]\n|score      = 2\u20130\n|report     = https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2017-12-09-toronto-fc-vs-seattle-sounders-fc/boxscore\n|team2      = [[Seattle Sounders FC]]\n|goals1     =\n* [[Jozy Altidore|Altidore]] {{goal|67}}\n* [[V\u00edctor V\u00e1zquez Solsona|V\u00e1zquez]] {{goal|90+4}}\n|goals2     =\n|stadium    = [[BMO Field]]\n|location   = [[Toronto]], Canada\n|attendance = 30,584\n|referee    = [[Allen Chapman]] ([[United States Soccer Federation|United States]])\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n{| width=92%\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _torontofc17h\n |pattern_b  = _torontofc17H\n |pattern_ra = _torontofc17h\n |pattern_sh = _torontofc17h\n |pattern_so = _torontofc17h\n |leftarm    = DD0000\n |body       = DD0000\n |rightarm   = DD0000\n |shorts     = DD0000\n |socks      = DD0000\n |title      = {{nowrap|Toronto FC}}\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la =\n |pattern_b  = _SOUNDERS_15h\n |pattern_ra =\n |pattern_sh =\n |pattern_so = _SOUNDERS_15h\n |leftarm    = 005695\n |body       = 628B18\n |rightarm  