*30 minutes of [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]] if necessary.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still level.\n*Seven named substitutes.\n*Maximum of three substitutions, with a fourth allowed in extra time.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nToronto FC became the first Canadian team to win the MLS Cup, and the first MLS team to complete a domestic [[treble (association football)|treble]], after winning the [[Canadian Championship]] and [[Supporters' Shield]] earlier in the season.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 9, 2017 |title=Toronto beats Seattle to win MLS Cup |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42282402 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=December 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213204714/http://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42282402 |archive-date=December 13, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Toronto received a $275,000 USD cash prize as winners, while Seattle was awarded $80,000.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |date=December 9, 2017 |title=MLS Cup win worth $275,000 in bonus cash for TFC |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/12/09/mls-cup-win-worth-275000-in-bonus-cash-for-tfc.html |work=Toronto Star |agency=The Canadian Press |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214124814/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/12/09/mls-cup-win-worth-275000-in-bonus-cash-for-tfc.html |archive-date=December 14, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Due to Toronto's win, the [[2019 CONCACAF Champions League]] berth reserved for the MLS Cup champions will instead go to the US based team (excluding other qualifiers) that finishes with the highest aggregate regular season points in 2017 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stejskal |first=Sam |date=September 22, 2017 |title=How CONCACAF Champions League qualifiers are determined in MLS |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/09/22/how-concacaf-champions-league-qualifiers-are-determined-mls |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=December 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026000625/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/09/22/how-concacaf-champions-league-qualifiers-are-determined-mls |archive-date=October 26, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Toronto was ineligible to qualify through the berth, which belongs to the [[United States Soccer Federation]], but qualified for the [[2018 CONCACAF Champions League]] after winning the 2017 Canadian Championship.<ref>{{cite news |last=Straus |first=Brian |date=April 6, 2017 |title=MLS clubs have resolution over qualifying for future CCL after format change |url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2017/04/06/concacaf-champions-league-ccl-qualifying-format-changes |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=December 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021071042/https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2017/04/06/concacaf-champions-league-ccl-qualifying-format-changes |archive-date=October 21, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Molinaro |first=John |date=July 24, 2017 |title=Champions League ambitions a sign of culture change at TFC |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/tfc-toronto-fc-bill-manning-concacaf-champions-league-mls-major-league-soccer/ |publisher=Sportsnet |accessdate=December 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171210123736/http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/tfc-toronto-fc-bill-manning-concacaf-champions-league-mls-major-league-soccer/ |archive-date=December 10, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Toronto was also qualified to host and play in the inaugural [[2018 Campeones Cup|Campeones Cup]], a new competition staged between the winners of the MLS Cup and the Mexican [[Campe\u00f3n de Campeones]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Peterson |first=Anne M. |date=13 March 2018 |title=Toronto FC to host first Campeones Cup as MLS, Mexico's Liga MX form partnership |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2018/03/13/toronto-fc-to-host-first-campeones-cup-as-mls-mexicos-liga-mx-form-partnership.html |agency=Associated Press |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=November 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626030815/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2018/03/13/toronto-fc-to-host-first-campeones-cup-as-mls-mexicos-liga-mx-form-partnership.html |archive-date=June 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Toronto played against [[Tigres UANL]] on September 19, 2018, and lost 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shoalts |first=David |date=September 19, 2018 |title=Mexico's Tigres get a little payback, defeat Toronto FC in Campeones Cup |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/article-mexicos-tigres-get-a-little-payback-defeat-toronto-fc-in-campeones/ |work=The Globe and Mail |accessdate=November 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109081517/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/article-mexicos-tigres-get-a-little-payback-defeat-toronto-fc-in-campeones/ |archive-date=November 9, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe day after the final, ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' mistakenly ran pre-scheduled advertisements on its website that promoted a victory parade and rally for the Sounders, which were later removed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Alexandra |date=December 11, 2017 |title=Seattle paper shows MLS \u2018victory\u2019 ads for Sounders |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/12/11/seattle-paper-shows-mls-victory-ads-for-sounders.html |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213162326/https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2017/12/11/seattle-paper-shows-mls-victory-ads-for-sounders.html |archive-date=December 13, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> As part of a pre-match wager between the mayors of the two cities, [[Seattle City Hall]] was lit in red on December 13.<ref>{{cite news |date=December 13, 2017 |title=Seattle City Hall illuminated in red to honor mayor's MLS Cup friendly bet with Toronto |url=http://komonews.com/news/local/seattle-city-hall-illuminated-in-red-to-honor-mayors-mls-cup-friendly-bet-with-toronto |publisher=[[KOMO-TV|KOMO 4 News]] |accessdate=December 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214071116/http://komonews.com/news/local/seattle-city-hall-illuminated-in-red-to-honor-mayors-mls-cup-friendly-bet-with-toronto |archive-date=December 14, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Toronto FC celebrated their victory with a parade two days after the final on December 11, traveling from [[Maple Leaf Square]] to [[Nathan Phillips Square]] in downtown Toronto. The parade was attended by a several thousand fans, as well as Toronto Mayor [[John Tory]], who declared the day as \"Reds Day\".<ref>{{cite news |date=December 11, 2017 |title=Toronto FC victory parade, fan rally take over downtown |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/toronto-fc-champion-parade-route-rally-1.4442569 |work=[[CBC News]] |accessdate=December 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212000809/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/toronto-fc-champion-parade-route-rally-1.4442569 |archive-date=December 12, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It was the second victory parade held in the city in as many weeks, as the [[Toronto Argonauts]] had won the [[Canadian Football League]]'s [[Grey Cup]] in November.<ref>{{cite news |last=McKenna |first=Ryan |date=December 11, 2017 |title=Chanting fans pack downtown Toronto to celebrate TFC's MLS Cup championship |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/sports-pmn/toronto-fc-to-hold-downtown-victory-parade-following-mls-cup-championship |work=The National Post |agency=The Canadian Press |accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Association football|Ontario}}\n{{MLSCup}}\n{{2017 in American soccer}}\n{{2017 in Canadian soccer}}\n{{Seattle Sounders FC matches}}\n{{Toronto FC matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mls Cup 2017}}\n[[Category:MLS Cup|2017]]\n[[Category:2017 Major League Soccer season]]\n[[Category: