{"title_page": "Paramount Home Entertainment", "text_new": "{{short description|US home video distribution company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}} \n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Paramount Home Entertainment\n| former_names        = Paramount Home Video (1976{{ndash}}2006)<br>Paramount Video (1982{{ndash}}1994)<br>Paramount Home Entertainment (1994{{ndash}}2011)\n| type                = [[Division (business)|Division]]\n| industry            = [[Home video|Home entertainment]]\n| founded             = {{start date and age|1976}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Hollywood, California|Hollywood]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| key_people          = Bob Buchi (President)\n| products            = Home video releases\n| services            = [[Home video]]<br>[[Digital distribution]]\n| parent              = [[Paramount Pictures]]<br>([[ViacomCBS]])\n| website             = [http://www.paramountmovies.com ParamountMovies.com]\n| footnotes           = <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediaplaynews.com/home-entertainment-divisions-change-names/|title=Home Media Distribution Divisions Change Names|last=Arnold|first=Thomas K.|date=2019-05-06|website=Media Play News|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Paramount Home Media Distribution''' '''(PHE)''' (formerly '''Paramount Home Entertainment''', '''Paramount Home Video''' and '''Paramount Video''') is the licensed content distribution arm of [[Paramount Pictures]], a division of [[ViacomCBS]].\n\nThe division oversees PPC\u2019s home entertainment and transactional digital distribution activities worldwide. The division is responsible for the sales, marketing and distribution of home entertainment content on behalf of [[Paramount Pictures]], [[Paramount Animation]], [[Paramount Television Studios]], [[Paramount Players]], [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]], [[MTV]], [[Nickelodeon]], [[Comedy Central]], [[CBS]], and applicable licensing and servicing of certain DreamWorks Pictures and Miramax titles. PHE additionally manages global licensing of studio content and transactional distribution across worldwide digital distribution platforms including online, mobile and portable devices and emerging technologies.<ref>{{Cite press release|title=Cinnabon & Paramount Home Media are Treating Fans to Ultimate Valentine\u2019s Night In|date=2019-02-06|url=https://www.cinnabon.com/newsroom/cinnabon-paramount-valentines-sweepstakes|access-date=2020-04-06|publisher=Cinnabon}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 2008, PHMD launched a direct-to-video label, Paramount Famous Productions (with the \"Famous\" part of the name a throwback to the days when the company was called Famous Players).\n\nIn the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Australia]], the Paramount Pictures film library were released by [[CIC Video]] alongside [[Universal Pictures]] until 1999 before CIC turned into two separate units: Paramount Home Entertainment International and Universal Studios Home Entertainment International.\n\nOn May 27, 2010, [[IFC Films]] struck another home video distribution deal with Paramount Home Media Distribution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paramount-home-media-ifc-films-798371|title=IFC Films Strikes Distribution Deal with Paramount Home Media Distribution|last=Kit|first=Broys|date=2015-05-27|website=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, it was announced that PHMD and [[Warner Home Video]] had signed a distribution deal, allowing Warner to gain U.S. and Canadian [[DVD]], [[Blu-ray]], [[UltraViolet (system)|UltraViolet]], [[Flixster]], and DVD-manufacturing-on-demand distribution rights to over 600 Paramount titles. The deal came into effect as of January 1, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2012/10/warner-bros-paramount-announce-home-media-distribution-deal-348266/|title=Warner Bros & Paramount Announce Home Media Distribution Deal|date=2012-10-04|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The deal however, has expired as of 2017 as evidenced by Paramount titles no longer appearing on Warner Home Video's web store. Distribution of the titles included in the Warner deal have since reverted to Paramount.\n\nIn February 2015, Paramount Home Media Distribution signed a distribution agreement with [[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment]], whereby the latter will distribute the former's titles overseas, particularly the territories where Paramount holds an office. The deal began on July 1, 2015, in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/universal-paramount-international-distribution-dvd-disc-1201372105/|title=Universal To Distribute Paramount\u2019s DVD & Blu-ray Discs Abroad|last=Lieberman|first=David|date=2015-02-12|website=Deadline|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2016-08-13}}</ref> \n\nIn June 2016, Paramount started releasing [[Ultra HD Blu-ray|Ultra HD Blu-ray discs]].\n\nFollowing [[ViacomCBS]] purchasing 49% stake in [[Miramax]] in 3 April 2020, PHE obtaining distribution rights to the entire Miramax library, as well as pre-2005 [[Dimension Films]] library.\n\n==HD DVD and Blu-ray support==\nParamount brands the majority of its HD content under the label 'Paramount High Definition' which is seen both on the title box cover and as an in-movie opening. Films from Paramount subsidiaries such as [[Nickelodeon Movies]] and [[MTV Films]] as well as from former sister studio [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] use no special branding, [[Paramount Vantage]] (another subsidiary) releases only select titles under the Paramount High Definition banner.\n\nIn October 2005, Paramount announced that it would be supporting the [[High-definition video|HD]] video format [[Blu-ray]] in addition to rival format [[HD DVD]], becoming the first studio to release on both formats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2005-10-03-paramount-says-yes-to-both-blu-ray-and-hd-dvd.html|title=Paramount says yes to both Blu-ray and HD DVD \u2013 Engadget|last=Rojas|first=Peter|date=2005-10-03|website=Engadget|url-status=live|accessdate=2010-01-07}}</ref> Its first four HD DVD releases came in July 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hddvd.highdefdigest.com/releasedates_historical.html|title=Historical HD DVD Release Dates|website=High Def Digest|url-status=live|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref> and it released four titles on Blu-ray two months later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bluray.highdefdigest.com/releasedates_historical.html|title=Historical Blu-ray Release Dates|website=High Def Digest|url-status=live|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref> In August 2007, Paramount (along with DreamWorks and [[DreamWorks Animation]]) announced their exclusive support for HD DVD.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/21/technology/21disney.html|title=Two Studios to Support HD DVD Over Rival|date=2007-08-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2007-08-21|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> However, when other studios eventually dropped HD DVD and players for the technology stopped being manufactured, Paramount switched to Blu-ray. In May 2008, it released three titles on Blu-ray and continues to release its high-definition discs in that format exclusively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2008-05-19-blu-ray-releases-on-may-20th-2008.html|title=Blu-ray releases on May 20th, 2008|last=Drawbaugh|first=Ben|date=2008-05-19|website=Engadget|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731151117/http://www.engadgethd.com/2008/05/19/blu-ray-releases-on-may-20th-2008/|archive-date=2009-07-31|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://www.paramountmovies.com/\n*{{imdb company|id=0381742|company=Paramount Home Media Distribution}}\n*{{imdb company|id=0051891|company=Paramount Home Video}}\n*{{imdb company|id=0142164|company=Paramount Home Entertainment}}\n*https://www.facebook.com/ParamountMovies/\n\n{{Viacom}}\n{{Region 1 home video}}\n{{Region 3 home video}}\n\n[[Category:American companies established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Home video companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Home video distributors]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures]]\n[[Category:ViacomCBS subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1976]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|US home video distribution company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}} \n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Paramount Home Entertainment\n| former_names        = Paramount Home Video (1976{{ndash}}2006)<br>Paramount Video (1982{{ndash}}1987)<br>Paramount Home Media Distribution (2011{{ndash}}2019)\n| type                = [[Division (business)|Division]]\n| industry            = [[Home video|Home entertainment]]\n| founded             = {{start date and age|1976}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Hollywood, California|Hollywood]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| key_people          = Bob Buchi (President)\n| products            = Home video releases\n| services            = [[Home video]]<br>[[Digital distribution]]\n| parent              = [[Paramount Pictures]]<br>([[ViacomCBS]])\n| website             = [http://www.paramountmovies.com ParamountMovies.com]\n| footnotes           = <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediaplaynews.com/home-entertainment-divisions-change-names/|title=Home Entertainment Divisions Change Names|last=Arnold|first=Thomas K.|date=2019-05-06|website=Media Play News|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Paramount Home Entertainment''' '''(PHE)''' (formerly '''Paramount Home Media Distribution''', '''Paramount Home Video''' and '''Paramount Video''') is the licensed content distribution arm of [[Paramount Pictures]], a division of [[ViacomCBS]].\n\nThe division oversees PPC\u2019s home entertainment and transactional digital distribution activities worldwide. The division is responsible for the sales, marketing and distribution of home entertainment content on behalf of [[Paramount Pictures]], [[Paramount Animation]], [[Paramount Television Studios]], [[Paramount Players]], [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]], [[MTV]], [[Nickelodeon]], [[Comedy Central]], [[CBS]], and applicable licensing and servicing of certain DreamWorks Pictures and Miramax titles. PHE additionally manages global licensing of studio content and transactional distribution across worldwide digital distribution platforms including online, mobile and portable devices and emerging technologies.<ref>{{Cite press release|title=Cinnabon & Paramount Home Media are Treating Fans to Ultimate Valentine\u2019s Night In|date=2019-02-06|url=https://www.cinnabon.com/newsroom/cinnabon-paramount-valentines-sweepstakes|access-date=2020-04-06|publisher=Cinnabon}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 2008, PHMD launched a direct-to-video label, Paramount Famous Productions (with the \"Famous\" part of the name a throwback to the days when the company was called Famous Players).\n\nIn the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Australia]], the Paramount Pictures film library were released by [[CIC Video]] alongside [[Universal Pictures]] until 1999 before CIC turned into two separate units: Paramount Home Entertainment International and Universal Studios Home Entertainment International.\n\nOn May 27, 2010, [[IFC Films]] struck another home video distribution deal with Paramount Home Media Distribution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paramount-home-media-ifc-films-798371|title=IFC Films Strikes Distribution Deal with Paramount Home Media Distribution|last=Kit|first=Broys|date=2015-05-27|website=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, it was announced that PHMD and [[Warner Home Video]] had signed a distribution deal, allowing Warner to gain U.S. and Canadian [[DVD]], [[Blu-ray]], [[UltraViolet (system)|UltraViolet]], [[Flixster]], and DVD-manufacturing-on-demand distribution rights to over 600 Paramount titles. The deal came into effect as of January 1, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2012/10/warner-bros-paramount-announce-home-media-distribution-deal-348266/|title=Warner Bros & Paramount Announce Home Media Distribution Deal|date=2012-10-04|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The deal however, has expired as of 2017 as evidenced by Paramount titles no longer appearing on Warner Home Video's web store. Distribution of the titles included in the Warner deal have since reverted to Paramount.\n\nIn February 2015, Paramount Home Media Distribution signed a distribution agreement with [[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment]], whereby the latter will distribute the former's titles overseas, particularly the territories where Paramount holds an office. The deal began on July 1, 2015, in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/universal-paramount-international-distribution-dvd-disc-1201372105/|title=Universal To Distribute Paramount\u2019s DVD & Blu-ray Discs Abroad|last=Lieberman|first=David|date=2015-02-12|website=Deadline|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=2016-08-13}}</ref> \n\nIn June 2016, Paramount started releasing [[Ultra HD Blu-ray|Ultra HD Blu-ray discs]].\n\nFollowing [[ViacomCBS]] purchasing 49% stake in [[Miramax]] in 3 April 2020, PHE obtaining distribution rights to the entire Miramax library, as well as pre-2005 [[Dimension Films]] library.\n\n==HD DVD and Blu-ray support==\nParamount brands the majority of its HD content under the label 'Paramount High Definition' which is seen both on the title box cover and as an in-movie opening. Films from Paramount subsidiaries such as [[Nickelodeon Movies]] and [[MTV Films]] as well as from former sister studio [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] use no special branding, [[Paramount Vantage]] (another subsidiary) releases only select titles under the Paramount High Definition banner.\n\nIn October 2005, Paramount announced that it would be supporting the [[High-definition video|HD]] video format [[Blu-ray]] in addition to rival format [[HD DVD]], becoming the first studio to release on both formats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2005-10-03-paramount-says-yes-to-both-blu-ray-and-hd-dvd.html|title=Paramount says yes to both Blu-ray and HD DVD \u2013 Engadget|last=Rojas|first=Peter|date=2005-10-03|website=Engadget|url-status=live|accessdate=2010-01-07}}</ref> Its first four HD DVD releases came in July 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hddvd.highdefdigest.com/releasedates_historical.html|title=Historical HD DVD Release Dates|website=High Def Digest|url-status=live|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref> and it released four titles on Blu-ray two months later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bluray.highdefdigest.com/releasedates_historical.html|title=Historical Blu-ray Release Dates|website=High Def Digest|url-status=live|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref> In August 2007, Paramount (along with DreamWorks and [[DreamWorks Animation]]) announced their exclusive support for HD DVD.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/21/technology/21disney.html|title=Two Studios to Support HD DVD Over Rival|date=2007-08-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2007-08-21|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> However, when other studios eventually dropped HD DVD and players for the technology stopped being manufactured, Paramount switched to Blu-ray. In May 2008, it released three titles on Blu-ray and continues to release its high-definition discs in that format exclusively.<